"Palmer M.D., Haines K., Tett S.F.B., Ansell T.J.","Isolating the signal of ocean global warming",2007,"Geophysical Research Letters","34","23", L23610,"","",,,10.1029/2007GL031712,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-39049108657&partnerID=40&md5=b0879832275ee136a24ade8cf81ba26b","Hadley Centre for Climate Change, Met Office, FitzRoy Road, Exeter EX1 3PB, United Kingdom; Environmental Systems Science Centre, Harry Pitt Building, Whiteknights, Reading RG6 6AL, United Kingdom; Department of Earth Science, University of Edinburgh, Grant Institute, West Mains Road, Edinburgh EH9 3JW, United Kingdom","Palmer, M.D., Hadley Centre for Climate Change, Met Office, FitzRoy Road, Exeter EX1 3PB, United Kingdom; Haines, K., Environmental Systems Science Centre, Harry Pitt Building, Whiteknights, Reading RG6 6AL, United Kingdom; Tett, S.F.B., Department of Earth Science, University of Edinburgh, Grant Institute, West Mains Road, Edinburgh EH9 3JW, United Kingdom; Ansell, T.J., Hadley Centre for Climate Change, Met Office, FitzRoy Road, Exeter EX1 3PB, United Kingdom","Identifying the signature of global warming in the world's oceans is challenging because low frequency circulation changes can dominate local temperature changes. The IPCC fourth assessment reported an average ocean heating rate of 0.21 ± 0.04 Wm-2 over the period 1961-2003, with considerable spatial, interannual and inter-decadal variability. We present a new analysis of millions of ocean temperature profiles designed to filter out local dynamical changes to give a more consistent view of the underlying warming. Time series of temperature anomaly for all waters warmer than 14°C show large reductions in interannual to inter-decadal variability and a more spatially uniform upper ocean warming trend (0.12 Wm-2 on average) than previous results. This new measure of ocean warming is also more robust to some sources of error in the ocean observing system. Our new analysis provides a useful addition for evaluation of coupled climate models, to the traditional fixed depth analyses. Copyright 2007 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Atmospheric temperature; Global warming; Mathematical models; Time series analysis; Weather forecasting; Inter-decadal variability; Ocean global warming; Ocean temperature; Oceanography; annual variation; climate modeling; decadal variation; global warming; heating; Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change; temperature anomaly; temperature profile",,,,,,"AchutaRao, K.M., Santer, B.D., Gleckler, P.J., Taylor, K.E., Pierce, D.W., Barnett, T.P., Wigley, T.M.L., Variability of ocean heat uptake: Reconciling observations and models (2006) J. Geophys. Res, 111, pp. C05019. , doi:10.1029/2005JC003136; Barnett, T.P., Pierce, D.W., AchutaRao, K.M., Glecker, P.J., Santer, B.D., Gregory, J.M., Washington, W.M., Penetration of human-induced warming into the world's oceans (2005) Science, 309, pp. 284-287; Bindoff, N. L., et al. (2007), in Climate Change 2007: The Physical Science Basis. Contribution of Working Group I to the Fourth Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, edited by S. D. Solomon et al., chap. 5, pp. 385-432, Cambridge Univ. Press, New YorkConkright, M. E., et al. (2002), World Ocean Database 2001, 1, Introduction, NOAA Atlas NESDIS 42, 159 pp., U.S. Gov. Print. Off., Washington D. CDavis, R.E., Sherman, J.T., Dufour, J., Profiling ALACEs and other advances in autonomous subsurface floats (2001) J. Atmos. Oceanic Technol, 18, pp. 982-993; Gillett, N.P., Allan, R.J., Ansell, T.J., Detection of external influence on sea level pressure with a multi-model ensemble (2005) Geophys. Res. Lett, 32, pp. L19714. , doi:10.1029/2005GL023640; Gouretski, V., Koltermann, K.P., How much is the ocean really warming? (2007) Geophys. Res. Lett, 34, pp. L01610. , doi:10.1029/ 2006GL027834; Gregon, J.M., Banks, H.T., Stott, P.A., Lowe, J.A., Palmer, M.D., Simulated and observed decadal variability in ocean heat content (2004) G